BODY.RESULTS.INSULIN RESISTANCE.
We used the hyperinsulinaemic euglycaemic clamp technique to obtain GIR values during both placebo and LPS conditions. There was no significant correlation between the increase in sCD163 concentrations (ΔsCD163 = sCD163LPS − sCD163placebo) and the increase in insulin resistance (ΔGIR = GIRplacebo − GIRLPS) during LPS conditions compared with placebo (Fig. 2A). However, when excluding the abovementioned outlier, there was a significant (simple linear regression P < 0.001) positive correlation between ΔsCD163 and ΔGIR (Fig. 2B).
Figure 2Insulin resistance and sCD163. The change in plasma concentrations of sCD163 (ΔsCD163 = sCD163LPS − sCD163placebo) and the change in glucose infusion rates during the hyperinsulinemic euglycemic clamp period (GIR, ΔGIR = GIRplacebo − GIRLPS) during LPS and placebo exposures are shown for the eight test subjects (A). A parametric linear regression analysis showed no significant correlation between ΔsCD163 and ΔGIR (P = 0.8). N = 8. When excluding the outlier (marked with a red cross), parametric linear regression showed a significant (P < 0.001, r2 = 0.87) positive correlation between ΔGIR (insulin resistance) and ΔsCD163 (B). N = 7.


BODY.RESULTS.LIPID METABOLISM.
There was a significant positive correlation between plasma concentrations of FFA (P < 0.005), lipid oxidation rates (P = 0.007), Rapalmitate (P < 0.005) and plasma concentrations of BHB (P = 0.006) with the plasma concentrations of sCD163 at time ≈ 240 min (Fig. 3 and Table 1). Additionally, sCD163 concentrations also had a significant (P < 0.005) positive correlation with the phosphorylated amount of HSL (involved in lipolysis) in SAT biopsies (Fig. 3).
